4":"1294","1293":"1293","1260":"1260","Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Ardevora, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pettit","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly southeastern): variant of   Petit  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Petit","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Alain, Michel, Normand, Mireille, Philippe, Pierre, Achille, Armand, Jean Claude, Jean Jacques, Ketly, Adrien.","French, Walloon, Catalan, English, Jewish (from southern France), West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Mauritian: from (Old) French, Catalan, and Middle English <i>petit</i> ‘small’, hence a nickname for a small man (or an ironic nickname for a big man), or a distinguishing name for the younger of two bearers of the same personal name. Compare   Little  ,   Petee  , and   Petite  .","History: Charles Petit from Anneville-Ambourville in Seine-Maritime, France, married Jeanne Rossignol (Martin and Renée Desjardins) in Quebec City, QC, in 1670. Nicolas Petit <i>dit</i> Lapré/Laprée from Le Gué-d'Alleré in Charente-Maritime, France, married Marie Pouponnel in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1656. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Gobin from Lyon in Rhône married Marguerite Véron in Trois-Rivières, QC, in 1692. Pierre Petit <i>dit</i> Saint-Pierre from Évreux in Eure, France, married Judith Miville in Quebec City, QC, in 1758; see also   St. Pierre  . — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Pettet","meanings":["English: variant of   Pettit  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Pettit was born in 1293, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Petitt l, was 34 and his mother, Amicia L'Arcedekne, was 34. He married Joan in 1322, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1384, at the age of 91."},"et":{"1293–1384":"1293–1384","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1287–Female":"1287–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1343–Female":"1343–Surnud","1260–1294":"1260–1294","1259–1294":"1259–1294","1259":"1259","1302":"1302","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1287":"1287","abt 1294":"umbes 1294","1384":"1384","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1260":"1260","Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Ardevora, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Philleigh, Cornwall, England":"Philleigh, Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1293–1384":"1293–1384","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1287–Female":"1287–Kuollut","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","1343–Female":"1343–Kuollut","1260–1294":"1260–1294","1259–1294":"1259–1294","1259":"1259","1302":"1302","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1287":"1287","abt 1294":"noin 1294","1384":"1384","1285":"1285","1295":"1295","1294":"1294","1293":"1293","1260":"1260","Raleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Raleigh, Devon, England":"Devon, England","Ardevora, Cornwal